\f0\b\fs24 \cf2 After the Is-Ought Gap\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 The is-ought gap only arises in the minds of certain philosophers. In the minds of other philosophers, there is simply no problem. \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf2 If the is-ought gap is a problem for you, then there is also a nature-normativity gap. You probably think all natural facts are non-normative and all normative \'93facts\'94 are non-factual \'97 that is, if you don\'92t believe in such facts, then all normative concepts are non-natural concepts that either have no referent or have a natural referent.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf2 However, if the is-ought gap is not a problem for you, then there is a distinction (but not a gap) between natural descriptions and natural norms. You probably think some norms are descriptive (cars can drive) while some descriptions are normative (dogs have four legs. If a mother dog is pregnant, you can expect she ought to have a pup with four legs.)\
\
The is-ought gap was not a problem for many philosophers. It simply did not concern them. I mean \'93concern\'94 here in both senses; they did not pay it any attention and they did not feel great consternation over it. They didn\'92t bother with it; and it didn\'92t bother them. \
\
Yet nowadays in analytic philosophy it is pretty widely felt that the is-ought gap is either insurmountable or that it is well nigh impossible to surmount. Hence, we are either forced to become normative non-naturalists (if we want to retain moral realism) or we are forced to go in for moral anti-realism (if we want to retain naturalism). Simon Blackburn offers us a quasi-realist alternative that, to hear him tell the story, is virtually the only option if we are genuinely committed to naturalism but still pine for realism. \
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl360\slmult1\pardirnatural
\cf0 He says naturalists demand: "To ask no more of the world than we already know is there\'97the ordinary features of things on the basis of which we make decisions about them, like or dislike them, fear them and avoid them, desire them and seek them out. It asks no more than this: a natural world, and patterns of reaction to it."[@blackburn1985spreading] \
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl360\slmult1\pardirnatural
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
My question for this article is simple: What happened? If the is-ought gap arises only in the minds of certain philosophers, what thought precipitates it? If philosophers of ancient days did not bother with it, were they too daft to notice the problem? Were they innocent of some confusion that plagues us? \
\
My goal in this brief discussion is to argue, with a very modest amount of rummaging through philosophical history, that the is-ought gap is no longer a problem. The historical anomaly that is the is-ought gap ought to be put to bed. We can preserve it, if we wish, in a glass case, as it were, for future philosophy students to observe and perhaps autopsy. But it should be preserved as a dead thing, not a live threat. \
\
It is not difficult to state, with some approximation, the time in history when the is-ought gap began to arise in force and cause great trouble among philosophers. \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The is-ought gap arises at precisely the moment (or just after) that a certain picture of nature arises in one\'92s mind. It is the picture of what John McDowel calls \'93bald nature.\'94 A dialogue between two character sin Andrei Tarkovsky\'92s film *Stalker* encapsulates this dreary picture quite well. \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

