What should we call this picture of nature? Some polemicists will be quick to call it "the scientific" picture. They are wrong, and deadly wrong. They have no right to sully a noble word like "science" with this association, as I shall argue. The terminological issue is no mean issue. Some others call this picture Newtonian. However, Alvin Plantinga has persuasively inveighed against smearing Newton so. Newton was a dyed-in-the-wool supernaturalist who believed the laws of nature were the laws of nature\'92s God. Plantinga, like a gentlemen, offers an alternative: Laplacian nature. I think this is the choicest name for this picture of nature. \
\
With labels settled, we can return to the question. As soon as the picture of Laplacian nature was presented to you, the is-ought gap became fatal. As soon as someone told you a story, or you had a sort of miserific vision of nature as bald, mechanical, cold, meaningless, dry, disenchanted, interminable, fatal, dull, dreary, and dead \'97 you became a normative non-naturalist or an anti-realist naturalist. \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
The thing to realize is that this conception of nature, the Laplacian one, is neither scientific nor natural. For  \'93nature\'94 is a word like \'93thing\'94 that can mean anything. And before we look at \'93everything\'94 all at once and determine what \'93everything\'94 is like in our world-picture, we should look at specific things. Before we decide what can possibly count as \'93natural\'94 and \'93non-natural,\'94 we should look at some actual natural things. \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The first thing to look at is any living organism \'97 say, fungus. Fungus is not a part of Laplacian nature. Bacteria are impossible in Laplace's nature. Reductionism of biological organisms to physical or mechanical systems has simply failed. In the heady days of the scientific revolution, perhaps, there was some sense in holding out hope that reductionism would come through in the end. But it has been 300 years, and we are not an inch further down the road of successful reduction. Indeed, we are miles further back. We now know what Newton, Hume, Laplace did not know \'97 that the biomass of microbial life outweighs mammalian life by an order of hundreds (Whitman 1998). And that the mitochondria of a single celled organism are more complicated than cars. Laplace simply lacked the imagination (or the prophetic power) to belief that all the variegated functions and forms of life on earth (and perhaps elsewhere) are something new, something unprecedented, something like a singularity in the cosmos. \
\
The second thing to look at is apes and dolphins. These fascinating creatures are nowhere to be found in the \'93impoverished arsenals of the [Laplacian] imagination\'94 (to borrow a fine-tipped phrase from Sir Richard Dawkins). \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf2 There is no \'93enchantment\'94 to this enchanting picture. It is the scientific picture, if biology, organic chemistry, primatology, ethology, sociology, or any of the other dozens of life sciences and social sciences are genuine sciences. To quote Dawkins again, a poet of science if there ever was one \'97 \'93The scientific world view is \'85 exciting\'85 poetic\'85 filled with sheer wonder\'85\'94 He may be a physicalist but but the belief that \'93physical\'94 just means \'93Laplacian\'94 is a superstition. If the \'93physical\'94 is the \'93Laplacian\'94 then the \'93physical\'94 excludes fungus, the ostrich, and us.\
\
Thomas Nagel\'92s delightfully simple, deceptively profound, and terrifyingly significant *Mind and Cosmos* is just one of a new windfall of modern philosophers who are scientific, naturalistic, and unapologetically non-Laplacian. The egg on the Laplacian face is not for Nagel not just life but consciousness, rationality, and morality. Laplace cannot, and never will be able to, account for them. \
\
So we live in a time after the is-ought gap. It did not exist in the ancient and medieval world. It was born, somewhere after the scientific revolution, in the minds of those with a genuine admiration for modern science who mistook the \'93scientific\'94 picture for the Laplacian one. However, it began to age \'97 and not gracefully either \'97 Somewhere around the discovery of the gene, or DNA, the dominant view of nature ceased to be the Laplacian one. Working scientists do not bother reducing things that are, to them, obviously fundamental properties of living organisms. These are not ghosts in every house or gods in every church; these are microbiomes that live on your body and outnumber your very cells. These are organs that pump blood to your brain so you can read these words.  The is-ought gap grew old and sickly in the heady days of reductionism, eliminative and monistic physicalism, and logical positivism. It is now barely alive on life support and gasping its last. I would dare to venture that this essay will help us all to collectively pull the plug. \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Since the rise of modern science, life, consciousness, rationality, and morality have not gone away. Life, consciousness, and the others are never going away. But life, consciousness, and the others are incompatible with the Laplacian picture. And without the Laplacian picture of nature, there is no is-ought gap. And we ought to reject the out-dated, unscientific, anti-naturalistic, dreadfully simplistic Laplacian picture. So we ought to realize there is no is-ought gap. }